    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Park Rampage, And a Mother's Fear</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Martin Fisch letter says mob violence against women in Central Park ws surely aggravated by lurid display of public drinking that was tolerated by city officials and police during Puerto Rican Day parade (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The mob violence in Central Park directed against defenseless women and others (news article, June 15) was surely aggravated by the lurid display of public drinking that was tolerated by city officials and the police. Not only is public consumption of alcohol a criminal offense, but the excessive displays of public drunkenness are also disgusting and almost always lead to violent acts, whether random or more specific.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The mob violence in Central Park directed against defenseless women and others (news article, June 15) was surely aggravated by the lurid display of public drinking that was tolerated by city officials and the police. Not only is public consumption of alcohol a criminal offense, but the excessive displays of public drunkenness are also disgusting and almost always lead to violent acts, whether random or more specific.</p>
        <p>Once public drunkenness gets out of hand, it is difficult to control. The police must do a better job of identifying and arresting the first offenders before a series of violent acts takes place.</p>
        <p>MARTIN FISCH  Andover, Mass., June 15, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
